hich helped him to reshape and deepen his social and political ideas. Hence, the [[Qeysar (film)|''Qeysar'']] outbreak made him give up his studies and come back to Iran to pursue his cinematic career. The quality of his work in ''Qeysar'', along with the success of the film at the box office and among the critics, put more attention on the music for films in Iran which until that day was not taken seriously by the Iranian film industry. The following year, he won the Best Film Score award for [[Qeysar (film)|''Qeysar'']] at the second \"Sepas Awards\" ceremony which would be repeated the next year for his third collaboration with [[Masoud Kimiai]] (''Reza Motori'', 1970). His film scores continued with ''Toughi'' ([[Ali Hatami]], 1970), ''Window'' (Jalal Moghaddam, 1970), ''[[Dash Akol]]'' (Masoud Kimiai, 1971), ''Topoli'' (Reza Mirlohi, 1972), ''Balouch'' (Masoud Kimiai, 1972), ''Soil'' (Masoud Kimiai, 1973), ''[[Tangna]]'' ([[Amir Naderi]], 1973), and ''The Deers'' ''(Gavaznha)'' (Masoud Kimiai, 1974).<ref>{{Cite book|title= Displaced allegories : post-revolutionary Iranian cinema|last= Negar.|first= Mottahedeh|date= 2008|publisher= Duke University Press|isbn= 9780822342755|location= Durham|oclc= 226361821}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url= https://archive.org/details/closeupiranianci0000daba|title= Close up : Iranian cinema, past, present, and future|last= 1951-|first= Dabashi, Hamid|date= 2001|publisher= Verso|isbn= 1859843328|location= London|oclc= 48432961|url-access= registration}}</ref>\n\n=== Pop music ===\nIn 1965 and after working on the [[National Iranian Radio and Television|National Iranian Radio]] and later the [[University of Tehran]] orchestra, he began his collaboration with the Tanin Recording Studio (the first private recording studio in Iran), and along with his comrades contributed to shape a new atmosphere in the [[Iranian pop music]]. In parallel to his cinematic activities and through his well-known songs such as \"Friday\" and \"Nightly 1\", he tried to represent Iranian people by picturing their pains and sorrows under the totalitarian Shah\u2019s regime. In 1973, he was sentenced to jail for his social and political ideas. However, after his release he would not remain silent and with his works (songs such as \"Gonjishkak-e Ashi Mashi\", \"Childish (Koudakaneh)\", \"Nightly 2\" or \"Friday for Friday\"), he accompanied and supported people in the upcoming revolution.<ref>{{Cite book|title= Iranian Music and Popular Entertainment: From Motrebi to Losanjelesi and Beyond|last= Breyley|first= G. J.|last2= Fatemi|first2= Sasan|date= 2015-11-26|publisher= Routledge|isbn= 9780415575126|location= New York, NY Abingdon, Oxon OX|language= English}}</ref><ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url= http://www.bbc.com/persian/tv/2010/11/101124_hardtalk_esfandiar_monfaredzadeh|title= \u0628\u0647 \u0639\u0628\u0627\u0631\u062a \u062f\u06cc\u06af\u0631: \u06af\u0641\u062a\u06af\u0648 \u0628\u0627 \u0627\u0633\u0641\u0646\u062f\u06cc\u0627\u0631 \u0645\u0646\u0641\u0631\u062f\u0632\u0627\u062f\u0647|website= BBC Persian|language= fa-IR|access-date= 2018-03-01}}</ref>\n\n=== Institute for the Intellectual Development of Children and Young Adults ===\nIn 1970, he joined the \u201c[[Institute for the Intellectual Development of Children and Young Adults]]\" where he contributed to establish the Children\u2019s Film Training Center as well as writing music for audio books, animations, and short films produced by the institute.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.iranicaonline.org/articles/kanun-e-parvares-e-fekri-e-kudakan-va-nowjavanan|title=K\u0100NUN-E PARVARE\u0160-E FEKRI-E Encyclopaedia Iranica|last=electricpulp.com|website=www.iranicaonline.org|language=en|access-date=2018-04-08}}</ref>\n\n== Exile ==\nShortly after the [[Iranian Revolution]] in February 1979, he concluded that this was not what he has wished for, so he expressed his concerns with the songs \"Unity\" and \"Whisper\". He decided to leave Iran and go to a self-imposed exile which continues to this day.<ref name=\":0\" /> During the exile, his artistic activities were extremely limited; however, he still believes in change for his country and his people.\n\n==Selected filmography==\n* ''Keep the Flight in Mind'' (2012)\n* ''Iranian Taboo'' (2011)\n* [[Epitaph (2004 film)|''Epitaph'']] (2004)\n* ''Sobh-e Khakestar'' (1977)\n* ''[[Gavaznha]]'' (1976) \u2013 aka ''The Deers''\n* [[Ghazal (1975 film)|''Ghazal'']] (1975)\n* ''Haft-tir-ha-ye Choubi'' (1975)\n* ''Pesar-e Sharghi'' (1975)\n* [[Ali Akbar Sadeghi|''Rokh'']] (1974)\n* ''Nefrin'' (1973)\n* ''[[Tangna]]'' (1973) \u2013 aka ''Strait''\n* ''Balouch'' (1972)\n* ''Khak'' (1972) \u2013 aka ''The Soil''\n* [[Topoli (film)|''Topoli'']] (1972)\n* [[Dash Akol (film)|''Dash Akol'']] (1971)\n* ''Khastegar'' (1971) \u2013 aka ''The Suitor''\n* ''[[Khodahafez Rafigh]]'' (1971) \u2013 aka ''Goodbye, Friend!''\n* ''Toughi'' (1971)\n* [[Parviz Sayyad|''Hassan Kachal'']] (1970)\n* [[The Window (1970 film)|''The Window'']] (1970)\n* ''Raqqase-ye Shahr'' (1970)\n* ''[[Reza Motorcyclist|Reza Motori]]'' (1970) \u2013 aka ''Reza, the Motorcyclist''\n* ''Amou Sibilou'' (1969)\n* [[Qeysar (film)|''Qeysar'']] (1969)\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[https://www.monfaredzadehmusic.com/ Esfandiar Monfaredzadeh's official website]\n*[https://open.spotify.com/artist/5dMporZK1yIzJNLfBrAeiO Esfandiar Monfaredzadeh on Spotify]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCoog1sFqVdt7ARdVh0hDYQA/featured Esfandiar Monfaredzadeh on Youtube]\n*{{IMDb name|0597960}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Monfaredzadeh, Esfandiar}}\n[[Category:Iranian composers]]\n[[Category:Iranian film score composers]]\n[[Category:1941 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Iranian emigrants to Sweden]]\n[[Category:Iranian music arrangers]]\n", "name_user": "Atlantic306", "label": "safe", "comment": "short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Esfandiar_Monfaredzadeh"}
{"title_page": "Baba Is You", "text_new": "{{Short description|2019 puzzle video game}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Baba Is You\n| image = BaBa_is_You_Logo.png\n| caption = \n| developer = Hempuli\n| publisher = Hempuli\n| programmer = Arvi Teikari\n| designer = Arvi Teikari\n| composer = Arvi Teikari\n| platforms = {{plainlist|\n* [[Microsoft Windows]]\n* [[Linux]]\n* [[macOS]]\n* [[Nintendo Switch]]\n}}\n| engine = [[Multimedia Fusion 2]]\n| released = 13 March 2019\n| genre = [[Puzzle video game|Puzzle]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n| alt = The phrase \"Baba Is You\" written in all caps in a hand-written style, similar to penciled-in block letters. \"Baba\" and \"You\" is in pink, while the \"Is\" is white.\n}}\n\n'''''Baba Is You''''' is a [[puzzle video game]] created by [[Finland|Finnish]] indie developer Arvi Teikari (known professionally as Hempuli), released on 13 March 2019 for [[personal computer|PC]] and [[Nintendo Switch]]. The game centers around the manipulation of \"rules\"\u2014represented by tiles with words written on them\u2014in order to allow the [[player character]], usually the titular Baba, to reach a specified goal.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:Baba is you gameplay.gif|thumb|left|The three blocks reading \"WALL IS STOP\" create a rule that prevents Baba (the white [[rabbit]], made the [[player character]] by the phrase \"BABA IS YOU\") from crossing wall tiles. Once the rule blocks are separated, the rule is no longer enforced, and Baba can pass through walls.|alt=A white rabbit, named Baba, is enclosed in all directions by walls. Outside of this enclosure is the phrase \"BABA IS YOU\", and inside the enclosure is the phrase \"WALL IS STOP\". Baba moves around, and attempts to walk past a wall, but fails. Then, Baba breaks the \"WALL IS STOP\" phrase, and is able to walk past it.]]\nThe player, usually, controls a character known as Baba, with exceptions in some levels. Each level contains various movable word tiles, corresponding to specific types of objects and obstacles on the field (such as Baba itself, the goal flag, walls and environmental hazards, and other creatures), linking [[Operator (computer programming)|operators]] such as \"is\" and \"and\", and verb tiles reflecting the properties of these objects (such as \"you\", which makes the object become controlled by the player, \"push\" to make them movable, \"stop\" to make them impassable, \"win\" to specify the goal, \"sink\" to make items drown in it, and so on). The objective of each level is for the player to reach the goal by manipulating these tiles to create or modify \"rules\" by which they behave. For example, the goal can be changed by moving \"is\" and \"win\" blocks to another object, and the player can travel through objects by removing the \"stop\" trait from them.<ref name=\":0\" /> Levels can force specific rules by placing their blocks in a corner, so they cannot be moved.<ref name=\":1\" /> The game contains over 200 levels.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Development and release ==\n[[File:Arvi Teikari GDC IGF 2018.png|thumb|Arvi Teikari accepting his [[Independent Games Festival]] Award in 2018|alt=Arvi Teikari speaking behind a podium. He is wearing a black shirt with many icons from the game, including a flag, a mushroom, the \"BABA\", \"IS\", and \"WIN\" operators, and Baba itself.]]\nThe theme of the 2017 [[Nordic Game Jam]] was \"Not There\", which prompted Teikari (a student at the [[University of Helsinki]] who had previously developed the [[Metroidvania]]-genre game ''[[Environmental Station Alpha]]'') to envision a game concept based on manipulating logic operators. He explained that levels were often created by brainstorming a \"cool\" or \"amusing\" solution, and then coming up with how the player would accomplish it. Teikari noted that \"the most satisfying moments in puzzle games are those which present the player with simple but hard-to-wrap-your-head-around situations, so that solving the puzzle is about figuring out that ''one'' neat trick/twist.\"<ref name=\":2\" />  As with his previous projects, the game was developed using [[Multimedia Fusion]] 2, and a [[Lua (programming language)|Lua]] scripting plugin; Teikari credited his friend Lukas Meller for help with the Lua implementations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/314548/Road_to_the_IGF_Hempuli_Oys_Baba_Is_You.php|title=Road to the IGF: Hempuli Oy's Baba Is You|last=Couture|first=Joel|date=|website=Gamasutra|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308163041/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/314548/Road_to_the_IGF_Hempuli_Oys_Baba_Is_You.php|archive-date=2018-03-08|url-status=live|access-date=2019-03-14|df=}}</ref>\n\nTeikari stated in 2017 that he planned to release the full game in 2018, and placed a development version of the title for download at [[itch.io]]. After ''Baba Is You'' won at the Independent Games Festival in March 2018, a [[video game clone|clone]] of the game was released by a French publisher on the [[App Store]], using nearly the same graphics and calling itself the same name. Teikari worked with the French division of [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] to remove the offending app.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/316145/IGF_Awardwinning_Baba_Is_You_cloned_before_it_was_even_released.php | title = IGF Award-winning Baba Is You cloned before it was even released | first = Alex | last = Wawro | date = 2018-04-04 | access-date = 2019-03-16 | work = [[Gamasutra]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190421000239/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/316145/IGF_Awardwinning_Baba_Is_You_cloned_before_it_was_even_released.php | archive-date = 2019-04-21 | url-status = live | df =  }}</ref>\n\nThe game, and a [[Nintendo Switch]] release, were focused upon in a [[Nintendo]] [[indie game]]s showcase presentation on 31 August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/nintendo-nindies-showcase-summer-2018-1202918718/|title=Nintendo Holds Nindies Showcase Summer 2018|last=Fogel|first=Stefanie|last2=Fogel|first2=Stefanie|date=2018-08-28|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829112824/https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/nintendo-nindies-showcase-summer-2018-1202918718/|archive-date=2018-08-29|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> ''Baba Is You'' was released on 13 March 2019, via [[Steam (software)|Steam]] for Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS, and on Nintendo Switch.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA cross-platform level editor, with online level sharing, is expected to be added to the game within 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/baba-is-you-has-a-cross-platform-level-editor-coming/ | title = Baba is You has a cross-platform level editor coming | first = Jonathan | last = Bolding | date = November 17, 2019 | accessdate = November 17, 2019 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = NS: 84/100<ref name=\"MC_NS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/baba-is-you |title=Baba Is You for Switch Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref><br />PC: 87/100<ref name=\"MC_PC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/baba-is-you |title=Baba Is You for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n|PCGUS=PC: 90/100<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/baba-is-you-review/|title=Baba is You review|last=Warr|first=Philippa|date=2019-03-15|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|PG=NS: 4.5/5<ref name=\":1\" />\n|GSpot=PC & NS: 7/10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/baba-is-you-review-game-changer/1900-6417109/|title=Baba is You Review - Game-Changer|first=Calum|last=Marsh|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Baba Is You'' won first place at the 2017 [[Nordic Game Jam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/a-puzzle-game-where-you-rewrite-the-rules-of-each-level-1833232432|title=A Puzzle Game Where You Rewrite The Rules Of Each Level|last=MacLeod|first=Riley|date=2019-03-13|website=[[Kotaku]]|access-date=2019-03-16}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Seumas McNally Grand Prize]] and won awards for \"Best Student Game\" and \"Excellence In Design\" at the 2018 [[IGF Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/night-in-the-woods-tops-igf-awards-student-game-baba-is-you-wins-big/|title=Night in the Woods tops IGF Awards, student game Baba Is You wins big|last=Donnelly|first=Joe|date=2018-03-22|website=PC Gamer|access-date=2019-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303155813/https://www.pcgamer.com/night-in-the-woods-tops-igf-awards-student-game-baba-is-you-wins-big/|archive-date=2019-03-03|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also nominated for \"Best Indie Game\" at the [[2019 Golden Joystick Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards|title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards|last=Tailby|first=Stephen|date=2019-09-20|website=Push Square|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref> for \"Indie Game of the Year\" at the [[Fun & Serious Game Festival|Titanium Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|title=Titanium Awards 2019|website=[[Fun & Serious Game Festival]]|access-date=2019-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121193654/https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|archive-date=2019-11-21|url-status=live}}</ref> and for \"Best Independent Game\" at [[The Game Awards 2019]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-nominees-full-list/1100-6471564/|title=The Game Awards 2019 Nominees Full List|last=Winslow|first=Jeremy|date=2019-11-19|website=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> and won the award for \"Outstanding Achievement in Game Design\" for the [[23rd Annual D.I.C.E. Awards]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/untitled-goose-game-wins-top-bill-at-the-2020-dice-awards|title=Untitled Goose Game Wins Top Bill at the 2020 D.I.C.E. Awards|last=Van Allen|first=Eric|date=2020-02-14|website=[[Eurogamer|USgamer]]|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> in addition, it was nominated for \"Gameplay Design, New IP\" at the [[NAVGTR Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://navgtr.org/2019-nominees/|title=2019 Nominees|website=[[NAVGTR Awards|National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]]|date=2020-01-13|accessdate=2020-01-21}}</ref> and for \"[[British Academy Games Award for Game Design|Game Design]]\" and \"Original Property\" at the [[16th British Academy Games Awards]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2020/mar/03/death-stranding-and-control-dominate-bafta-games-awards-nominations|title=Death Stranding and Control dominate Bafta games awards nominations|last=Stuart|first=Keith|date=2020-03-03|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2020-03-05}}</ref> and won the award for \"Best Design\" and the \"Innovation Award\" at the [[20th Game Developers Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/untitled-goose-game-wins-another-game-of-the-year-/1100-6474953/|title=Untitled Goose Game Wins Another Game Of The Year Award|last=Makuch|first=Eddie|date=2020-03-18|website=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The PC version of the game was among the best-selling new releases of the month on [[Steam (service)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/sale/2019_top_new|title=Best of 2019: New Releases|website=[[Steam (service)|Steam]]|publisher=[[Valve Corporation|Valve]]|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2019.12.28-165246/https://store.steampowered.com/sale/2019_top_new|archive-date=2019-12-28|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref>{{efn|Based on total revenue for the first two weeks on sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://steamcommunity.com/games/593110/announcements/detail/1708485146980406784 |title=A Look Back - The Best of 2019 |date=2019-12-26 |website=[[Steam (service)|Steam]] |publisher=[[Valve Corporation|Valve]] |access-date=2019-12-28 |archive-url=http://archive.today/2019.12.28-165922/https://steamcommunity.com/games/593110/announcements/detail/1708485146980406784 |archive-date=2019-12-28 |url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\n''Baba Is You'' received \"generally favorable reviews\", according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC_NS\" /><ref name=\"MC_PC\" /> ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' considered it \"one of the best puzzle video games in years\", with the reviewer observing that it \"asks me to toss my assumptions about how rules in video games work, to analyze how and why they exist in the first place. And that sort of reprogramming of my brain, oddly enough, happens best when the game is turned off.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/3/13/18263824/baba-is-you-review-nintendo-switch-pc|title=Baba Is You review: one of the best puzzle games in years|last=Plante|first=Chris|date=2019-03-13|website=Polygon|access-date=2019-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313181622/https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/3/13/18263824/baba-is-you-review-nintendo-switch-pc|archive-date=2019-03-13|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> ''[[Pocket Gamer]]'' was similarly positive, describing it as a \"ridiculously complex puzzler that has you questioning not only every decision you make, but how anyone managed to think up something so bizarre\", and concluding that it was one of the \"most inventive, exciting puzzle games you will ever play. It's beautifully simple in its graphics and its core design, but it'll make your brain hurt with how nonsensical the solutions appear to be.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/080068/baba-is-you-switch-review/|title=Baba is You Switch review - \"Puzzling perfection in every way\"|last=Cowley|first=Ric|date=|website=Pocket Gamer|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite conference | url= https://www.gdcvault.com/play/1026590/Reading-the-Rules-of-Baba | title = \tReading the Rules of 'Baba Is You' | first = Arvi | last = Teikari | date = March 20, 2020 | accessdate = March 24, 2020 | conference = [[Game Developers Conference]] 2020 }}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Gordon |first1=Lewis |title=Indie game makers open up about the money they actually make |work=[[The Verge]] |date=2019-10-09 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/10/9/20903139/indie-game-developers-creators-money-funding |language=en |accessdate=2019-10-12 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website|https://www.hempuli.com/Baba/}}\n*[https://hempuli.itch.io/baba-is-you Demo version]\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Game jam video games]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Programming games]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Finland]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|2019 puzzle video game}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date = April 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox video game\n| title = Baba Is You\n| image = BaBa_is_You_Logo.png\n| caption = \n| developer = Hempuli\n| publisher = Hempuli\n| programmer = Arvi Teikari\n| designer = Arvi Teikari\n| composer = Arvi Teikari\n| platforms = {{plainlist|\n* [[Microsoft Windows]]\n* [[Linux]]\n* [[macOS]]\n* [[Nintendo Switch]]\n}}\n| engine = [[Multimedia Fusion 2]]\n| released = 13 March 2019\n| genre = [[Puzzle video game|Puzzle]]\n| modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]]\n}}\n\n'''''Baba Is You''''' is a [[puzzle video game]] created by [[Finland|Finnish]] indie developer Arvi Teikari (known professionally as Hempuli), released on 13 March 2019 for [[personal computer|PC]] and [[Nintendo Switch]]. The game centers around the manipulation of \"rules\"\u2014represented by tiles with words written on them\u2014in order to allow the [[player character]], usually the titular Baba, to reach a specified goal.\n\n== Gameplay ==\n[[File:Baba is you gameplay.gif|thumb|left|The three blocks reading \"WALL IS STOP\" create a rule that prevents Baba (the white [[rabbit]], made the [[player character]] by the phrase \"BABA IS YOU\") from crossing wall tiles. Once the rule blocks are separated, the rule is no longer enforced, and Baba can pass through walls.]]\nThe player, usually, controls a character known as Baba, with exceptions in some levels. Each level contains various movable word tiles, corresponding to specific types of objects and obstacles on the field (such as Baba itself, the goal flag, walls and environmental hazards, and other creatures), linking [[Operator (computer programming)|operators]] such as \"is\" and \"and\", and verb tiles reflecting the properties of these objects (such as \"you\", which makes the object become controlled by the player, \"push\" to make them movable, \"stop\" to make them impassable, \"win\" to specify the goal, \"sink\" to make items drown in it, and so on). The objective of each level is for the player to reach the goal by manipulating these tiles to create or modify \"rules\" by which they behave. For example, the goal can be changed by moving \"is\" and \"win\" blocks to another object, and the player can travel through objects by removing the \"stop\" trait from them.<ref name=\":0\" /> Levels can force specific rules by placing their blocks in a corner, so they cannot be moved.<ref name=\":1\" /> The game contains over 200 levels.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Development and release ==\n[[File:Arvi Teikari GDC IGF 2018.png|thumb|right|Arvi Teikari accepting his [[Independent Games Festival]] Award in 2018]]\nThe theme of the 2017 [[Nordic Game Jam]] was \"Not There\", which prompted Teikari (a student at the [[University of Helsinki]] who had previously developed the [[Metroidvania]]-genre game ''[[Environmental Station Alpha]]'') to envision a game concept based on manipulating logic operators. He explained that levels were often created by brainstorming a \"cool\" or \"amusing\" solution, and then coming up with how the player would accomplish it. Teikari noted that \"the most satisfying moments in puzzle games are those which present the player with simple but hard-to-wrap-your-head-around situations, so that solving the puzzle is about figuring out that ''one'' neat trick/twist.\"<ref name=\":2\" />  As with his previous projects, the game was developed using [[Multimedia Fusion]] 2, and a [[Lua (programming language)|Lua]] scripting plugin; Teikari credited his friend Lukas Meller for help with the Lua implementations.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/314548/Road_to_the_IGF_Hempuli_Oys_Baba_Is_You.php|title=Road to the IGF: Hempuli Oy's Baba Is You|last=Couture|first=Joel|date=|website=Gamasutra|language=en|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180308163041/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/314548/Road_to_the_IGF_Hempuli_Oys_Baba_Is_You.php|archive-date=2018-03-08|url-status=live|access-date=2019-03-14|df=}}</ref>\n\nTeikari stated in 2017 that he planned to release the full game in 2018, and placed a development version of the title for download at [[itch.io]]. After ''Baba Is You'' won at the Independent Games Festival in March 2018, a [[video game clone|clone]] of the game was released by a French publisher on the [[App Store]], using nearly the same graphics and calling itself the same name. Teikari worked with the French division of [[Apple Inc.|Apple]] to remove the offending app.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/316145/IGF_Awardwinning_Baba_Is_You_cloned_before_it_was_even_released.php | title = IGF Award-winning Baba Is You cloned before it was even released | first = Alex | last = Wawro | date = 2018-04-04 | access-date = 2019-03-16 | work = [[Gamasutra]] | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20190421000239/https://www.gamasutra.com/view/news/316145/IGF_Awardwinning_Baba_Is_You_cloned_before_it_was_even_released.php | archive-date = 2019-04-21 | url-status = live | df =  }}</ref>\n\nThe game, and a [[Nintendo Switch]] release, were focused upon in a [[Nintendo]] [[indie game]]s showcase presentation on 31 August 2018.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/nintendo-nindies-showcase-summer-2018-1202918718/|title=Nintendo Holds Nindies Showcase Summer 2018|last=Fogel|first=Stefanie|last2=Fogel|first2=Stefanie|date=2018-08-28|website=Variety|language=en|access-date=2019-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180829112824/https://variety.com/2018/gaming/news/nintendo-nindies-showcase-summer-2018-1202918718/|archive-date=2018-08-29|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> ''Baba Is You'' was released on 13 March 2019, via [[Steam (software)|Steam]] for Microsoft Windows, Linux, and macOS, and on Nintendo Switch.<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":0\" />\n\nA cross-platform level editor, with online level sharing, is expected to be added to the game within 2020.<ref>{{cite web | url = https://www.pcgamer.com/baba-is-you-has-a-cross-platform-level-editor-coming/ | title = Baba is You has a cross-platform level editor coming | first = Jonathan | last = Bolding | date = November 17, 2019 | accessdate = November 17, 2019 | work = [[PC Gamer]] }}</ref>\n\n== Reception ==\n{{Video game reviews\n| MC = NS: 84/100<ref name=\"MC_NS\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/switch/baba-is-you |title=Baba Is You for Switch Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref><br />PC: 87/100<ref name=\"MC_PC\">{{cite web |url=https://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/baba-is-you |title=Baba Is You for PC Reviews |website=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=2020-03-10}}</ref>\n|PCGUS=PC: 90/100<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/baba-is-you-review/|title=Baba is You review|last=Warr|first=Philippa|date=2019-03-15|website=PC Gamer|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n|PG=NS: 4.5/5<ref name=\":1\" />\n|GSpot=PC & NS: 7/10<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/baba-is-you-review-game-changer/1900-6417109/|title=Baba is You Review - Game-Changer|first=Calum|last=Marsh|website=GameSpot|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-10}}</ref>\n}}\n\n''Baba Is You'' won first place at the 2017 [[Nordic Game Jam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://kotaku.com/a-puzzle-game-where-you-rewrite-the-rules-of-each-level-1833232432|title=A Puzzle Game Where You Rewrite The Rules Of Each Level|last=MacLeod|first=Riley|date=2019-03-13|website=[[Kotaku]]|access-date=2019-03-16}}</ref> It was nominated for the [[Seumas McNally Grand Prize]] and won awards for \"Best Student Game\" and \"Excellence In Design\" at the 2018 [[IGF Awards]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pcgamer.com/night-in-the-woods-tops-igf-awards-student-game-baba-is-you-wins-big/|title=Night in the Woods tops IGF Awards, student game Baba Is You wins big|last=Donnelly|first=Joe|date=2018-03-22|website=PC Gamer|access-date=2019-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190303155813/https://www.pcgamer.com/night-in-the-woods-tops-igf-awards-student-game-baba-is-you-wins-big/|archive-date=2019-03-03|url-status=live}}</ref> It was also nominated for \"Best Indie Game\" at the [[2019 Golden Joystick Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.pushsquare.com/news/2019/09/days_gone_rides_off_with_three_nominations_in_this_years_golden_joystick_awards|title=Days Gone Rides Off with Three Nominations in This Year's Golden Joystick Awards|last=Tailby|first=Stephen|date=2019-09-20|website=Push Square|access-date=2019-09-21}}</ref> for \"Indie Game of the Year\" at the [[Fun & Serious Game Festival|Titanium Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|title=Titanium Awards 2019|website=[[Fun & Serious Game Festival]]|access-date=2019-11-22|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191121193654/https://en.funandseriousgamefestival.com/awards/|archive-date=2019-11-21|url-status=live}}</ref> and for \"Best Independent Game\" at [[The Game Awards 2019]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/the-game-awards-2019-nominees-full-list/1100-6471564/|title=The Game Awards 2019 Nominees Full List|last=Winslow|first=Jeremy|date=2019-11-19|website=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=2019-11-20}}</ref> and won the award for \"Outstanding Achievement in Game Design\" for the [[23rd Annual D.I.C.E. Awards]];<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usgamer.net/articles/untitled-goose-game-wins-top-bill-at-the-2020-dice-awards|title=Untitled Goose Game Wins Top Bill at the 2020 D.I.C.E. Awards|last=Van Allen|first=Eric|date=2020-02-14|website=[[Eurogamer|USgamer]]|accessdate=2020-02-14}}</ref> in addition, it was nominated for \"Gameplay Design, New IP\" at the [[NAVGTR Awards]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://navgtr.org/2019-nominees/|title=2019 Nominees|website=[[NAVGTR Awards|National Academy of Video Game Trade Reviewers]]|date=2020-01-13|accessdate=2020-01-21}}</ref> and for \"[[British Academy Games Award for Game Design|Game Design]]\" and \"Original Property\" at the [[16th British Academy Games Awards]],<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/games/2020/mar/03/death-stranding-and-control-dominate-bafta-games-awards-nominations|title=Death Stranding and Control dominate Bafta games awards nominations|last=Stuart|first=Keith|date=2020-03-03|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|accessdate=2020-03-05}}</ref> and won the award for \"Best Design\" and the \"Innovation Award\" at the [[20th Game Developers Choice Awards]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/articles/untitled-goose-game-wins-another-game-of-the-year-/1100-6474953/|title=Untitled Goose Game Wins Another Game Of The Year Award|last=Makuch|first=Eddie|date=2020-03-18|website=[[GameSpot]]|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> The PC version of the game was among the best-selling new releases of the month on [[Steam (service)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://store.steampowered.com/sale/2019_top_new|title=Best of 2019: New Releases|website=[[Steam (service)|Steam]]|publisher=[[Valve Corporation|Valve]]|url-status=live|archive-url=http://archive.today/2019.12.28-165246/https://store.steampowered.com/sale/2019_top_new|archive-date=2019-12-28|access-date=2019-12-28}}</ref>{{efn|Based on total revenue for the first two weeks on sale.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://steamcommunity.com/games/593110/announcements/detail/1708485146980406784 |title=A Look Back - The Best of 2019 |date=2019-12-26 |website=[[Steam (service)|Steam]] |publisher=[[Valve Corporation|Valve]] |access-date=2019-12-28 |archive-url=http://archive.today/2019.12.28-165922/https://steamcommunity.com/games/593110/announcements/detail/1708485146980406784 |archive-date=2019-12-28 |url-status=live}}</ref>}}\n\n''Baba Is You'' received \"generally favorable reviews\", according to [[review aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=\"MC_NS\" /><ref name=\"MC_PC\" /> ''[[Polygon (website)|Polygon]]'' considered it \"one of the best puzzle video games in years\", with the reviewer observing that it \"asks me to toss my assumptions about how rules in video games work, to analyze how and why they exist in the first place. And that sort of reprogramming of my brain, oddly enough, happens best when the game is turned off.\"<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/3/13/18263824/baba-is-you-review-nintendo-switch-pc|title=Baba Is You review: one of the best puzzle games in years|last=Plante|first=Chris|date=2019-03-13|website=Polygon|access-date=2019-03-14|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190313181622/https://www.polygon.com/reviews/2019/3/13/18263824/baba-is-you-review-nintendo-switch-pc|archive-date=2019-03-13|url-status=live|df=}}</ref> ''[[Pocket Gamer]]'' was similarly positive, describing it as a \"ridiculously complex puzzler that has you questioning not only every decision you make, but how anyone managed to think up something so bizarre\", and concluding that it was one of the \"most inventive, exciting puzzle games you will ever play. It's beautifully simple in its graphics and its core design, but it'll make your brain hurt with how nonsensical the solutions appear to be.\"<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.pocketgamer.com/articles/080068/baba-is-you-switch-review/|title=Baba is You Switch review - \"Puzzling perfection in every way\"|last=Cowley|first=Ric|date=|website=Pocket Gamer|language=en|archive-url=|archive-date=|url-status=|access-date=2019-03-14}}</ref>\n\n== Notes ==\n{{Notelist}}\n\n== References ==\n* {{cite conference | url= https://www.gdcvault.com/play/1026590/Reading-the-Rules-of-Baba | title = \tReading the Rules of 'Baba Is You' | first = Arvi | last = Teikari | date = March 20, 2020 | accessdate = March 24, 2020 | conference = [[Game Developers Conference]] 2020 }}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n\n{{refbegin}}\n\n* {{Cite web |last1=Gordon |first1=Lewis |title=Indie game makers open up about the money they actually make |work=[[The Verge]] |date=2019-10-09 |url=https://www.theverge.com/2019/10/9/20903139/indie-game-developers-creators-money-funding |language=en |accessdate=2019-10-12 |df=mdy-all }}\n\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{official website|https://www.hempuli.com/Baba/}}\n*[https://hempuli.itch.io/baba-is-you Demo version]\n\n[[Category:2019 video games]]\n[[Category:Game jam video games]]\n[[Category:Indie video games]]\n[[Category:Linux games]]\n[[Category:MacOS games]]\n[[Category:Nintendo Switch eShop games]]\n[[Category:Programming games]]\n[[Category:Puzzle video games]]\n[[Category:Video games developed in Finland]]\n[[Category:Windows games]]\n", "name_user": "AntiGravityMaster", "label": "safe", "comment": "Alts.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Baba_Is_You"}
{"title_page": "Daughters of Africa", "text_new": "[[File:Daughters of Africa 1st editon cover.jpg|thumb|UK 1st edition hardback, 1992. Photograph by Suzanne Roden.]]\n{{italic title}}\n'''''Daughters of Africa: An International Anthology of Words and Writings by Women of African Descent from the Ancient Egyptian to the Present''''' is a compilation of [[orature]] and literature by more than 200 women from Africa and the African diaspora, edited and introduced by [[Margaret Busby]],<ref name=Bolden>Tonya Bolden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=-lwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT13&lpg=PT13&dq=%22daughters+of+africa%22+200+women&source=bl&ots=LVRNaM4dxY&sig=DSC5ZXzFB95-pCQ1FsM4KLyAq5o&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAmoVChMItJe82rygxwIVitYaCh3ziQ9d#v=onepage&q=%22daughters%20of%20africa%22%20200%20women&f=false \"Book Review: Two Types of Revelation \u2013 ''Daughters of Africa''\"], ''[[Black Enterprise]]'', March 1993, p. 12.</ref> who compared the process of assembling the volume to \"trying to catch a flowing river in a calabash\".<ref>\"Introduction\", ''Daughters of Africa'', p. xxix.</ref> First published in 1992,<ref name=KinnaReads>Kinna, [http://kinnareads.com/2010/09/24/daughters-of-africa-edited-by-margaret-busby/ \"Daughters of Africa edited by Margaret Busby\"], Kinna Reads, 24 September 2010.</ref> in London by [[Jonathan Cape]] (having been commissioned by Candida Lacey,<ref>Candida Lacey, [http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02690055.2017.1350365 \"Daughters of Africa Twenty-five years later\"], ''Wasafiri'', 32(4), November 2017, pp. 7\u20138.</ref> now publisher of [[Myriad Editions]]),<ref>Margaret Busby, [http://www.commonwealthwriters.org/granddaughters-of-africa-margaret-busby/ \"Granddaughters of Africa\"], [[Commonwealth Writers]], 19 March 2015.</ref> and in New York by [[Pantheon Books]], ''Daughters of Africa'' is regarded as a pioneering work,<ref>[http://www.african-writing.com/Sep/africanbritishprofile.htm#top Margaret Busby profile], African Writing in Britain.</ref><ref>[http://www.bocaslitfest.com/awards/henry-swanzy-award/ \"The 2015 Bocas Henry Swanzy Award Recipient: Margaret Busby, OBE\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702024441/http://www.bocaslitfest.com/awards/henry-swanzy-award/ |date=2 July 2015 }}, [[NGC Bocas Lit Fest]].</ref> covering a variety of genres \u2014 including fiction, essays, poetry, drama, memoirs and children's writing \u2014 and more than 1000 pages in extent.<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2051521.Daughters_of_Africa \"Daughters of Africa\"], [[Goodreads]].</ref> Arranged chronologically, beginning with traditional oral poetry,<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/84478303/ \"Anthology of black women writers printed\"], ''Journal Gazette'' (Mattoon, Illinois), 3 December 1992, p. 19.</ref> it includes work translated from African languages as well as from Dutch, French, German, Portuguese, Russian and Spanish.<ref>[http://whatsonafrica.org/50-books-by-african-women-that-everyone-should-read/ \"50 Books by African Women that Everyone Should Read\"], What's_On Africa, Royal African Society, 30 June 2014.</ref><ref>Meserette Kentake, [http://kentakepage.com/daughters-of-africa/ \"Daughters of Africa\"], Kentake Page, 17 December 2013.</ref>\n\nThe anthology's title derives from an 1831 declaration by [[Maria W. Stewart]] (1803\u20131880), the first [[African-American]] woman to give public lectures, in which she said: \"O, ye daughters of Africa, awake! awake! arise! no longer sleep nor slumber, but distinguish yourselves. Show forth to the world that ye are endowed with noble and exalted faculties.\"<ref>Maria W. Stewart (ed. Marilyn Richardson), [https://books.google.com/books?id=noSOhOOsNuUC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=maria+stewart+%22ye+daughters+of+africa%22&source=bl&ots=tuyBxyTqUE&sig=ZYGhcoSnPkaZTe-73tid8AVCvxQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAWoVChMIoa6CoLOtxwIVRrUaCh1igw9W#v=onepage&q=maria%20stewart%20%22ye%20daughters%20of%20africa%22&f=false \"Religion And The Pure Principles of Morality, The Sure Foundation On Which We Must Build\"], in ''America's First Black Woman Political Writer: Essays and Speeches''], [[Indiana University Press]], 1987, p. 30.</ref>\n\nA companion volume entitled '''''New Daughters of Africa''''' was published in 2019.<ref name=Myriad />\n\n==Reception==\n''Daughters of Africa'' was widely praised on publication. Reviewing the anthology for Black British newspaper ''The Weekly Journal'', Evie Arup wrote: \"''Daughters of Africa'' is a literary first. Never before has the work of women of African descent world-wide been gathered together in one volume. The breadth of this collection is startling.... This book should be required reading for any student of literature, and a standard reference book in school libraries, and, to paraphrase that well known slogan, 'every home should have one.'\"<ref>Evie Arup, \"Books: Daughters of Africa\", ''The Weekly Journal'' (Issue 29), 12 November 1992, p. 15.</ref> The reviewer from ''[[The Independent]]'', however, observed: \"This book may seem to be about literature but in the end it is as much a testament to language: its power to create attitudes as well as its potency as a means of expression.\"<ref>Patricia Lee, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/book-review-canon-to-the-right-of-them-canon-to-the-left-daughters-of-africa-ed-margaret-busby-1563049.html \"BOOK REVIEW / Canon to the right of them, canon to the left...\"], ''The Independent'', 12 December 1992.</ref> Described by ''[[The Observer]]'' as a \"glorious fat anthology that makes a history out of a selection, and puts an unsung group of people on the map\",<ref>[[Nicci Gerrard]], \"Anthologies\", ''The Observer'', 29 November 1992.</ref> according to ''[[Library Journal]]'', it is \"an invaluable text for courses on women writers and writers of African descent\",<ref name=B&N>[http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/daughters-of-africa-margaret-busby/1002938755#productInfoTabs \"Daughters of Africa: An International Anthology of Words and Writings by Women of African Descent and from the Ancient Egyptian to the Present\"], Editorial Reviews, Barnes & Noble.</ref> and Keneth Kinnamon in ''[[Callaloo (journal)|Callaloo]]'' saw it as \"impressive\", noting: \"Brief headnotes and long bibliographies enhance the value of this important volume.\"<ref>Keneth Kinnamon, \"Anthologies of African-American Literature from 1845 to 1994\", in ''Callaloo'', Vol. 20, No. 2 (Spring 1997), p. 468.</ref> [[Lorna Sage]] in the ''Independent on Sunday'' concluded that \"''Daughters of Africa'' has a paradoxical universality\",<ref>Lorna Sage, \"Deep roots in an impossible homeland\", The Sunday Review, ''Independent on Sunday'', 3 January 1993, p. 21.</ref> while ''[[The Washington Post Book World]]'' called it: \"A magnificent starting place for any reader interested in becoming part of the collective enterprise of discovering and uncovering the silent, forgotten, and underrated voices of black women.\"<ref name=WP>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/entertainment/books/1994/02/06/new-in-paperback/438e9308-0e92-44ef-a403-3fde2d87806a/ \"New in Paperback\"], ''The Washington Post'', 6 February 1994.</ref><ref>Shereen Ali, [http://m.guardian.co.tt/lifestyle/2015-04-29/sharing-our-voices \"Sharing Our Voices\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802132012/http://m.guardian.co.tt/lifestyle/2015-04-29/sharing-our-voices |date=2018-08-02 }}, ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]'', 29 April 2015.</ref>  The reviewer for ''[[Black Enterprise]]'' wrote: \"It is a landmark anthology.... Busby's first-of-a-kind anthology is a poignant reminder of how vast and varied the body of black women's writing is.\"<ref name=Bolden /> It has also been called \"groundbreaking\",<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/margaret-busby Margaret Busby profile], ''[[The Guardian]]''.</ref> \"one of the most significant assemblages of writers across the diaspora\"<ref>Carol Boyce Davies, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA384&lpg=PA384&dq=%22Daughters+of+Africa%22+%22margaret+busby%22&source=bl&ots=uqtNXKoCPA&sig=5BNdSUI3ahIcdmpA-st1pgEJ5mk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CJIBEOgBMBhqFQoTCJ_a55Cmn8cCFUTaGgod8QwMWQ#v=onepage&q=%22Daughters%20of%20Africa%22%20%22margaret%20busby%22&f=false \"Women and Literature in the African Diaspora\"], in Melvin Ember, Carol R. Ember, Ian Skoggard (eds), ''Encyclopedia of Diasporas: Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World, Volume 1'', Springer Science and Business Media Inc., 2005, p. 384.</ref> and \"the ultimate reference guide to the writing of 'daughters of Africa'\".<ref>Sharmilla Beezmohun, [http://www.wasafiri.org/pages/content/index.asp?PageID=307 \"Twenty-Five most influential books\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084050/http://www.wasafiri.org/pages/content/index.asp?PageID=307 |date=2016-03-04 }}, ''[[Wasafiri]]'', 2009.</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' review by [[Maya Jaggi]] stated: \"With rare exceptions, anthologies of black writing and of women's writing have given the impression that there was very little literary endeavour by black women before the 1980s. Margaret Busby's impressive and imaginative selection of 'words and writings', ''Daughters of Africa'', finally destroys that misconception, while tracing continuities within a tradition of women's writing, deriving from Africa yet stretching across continents and centuries.\"<ref name=Jaggi>Maya Jaggi, \"Ain't I a woman\", ''The Times Literary Supplement'', 11 December 1992.</ref> Jaggi goes on to say: \"Some writings (such as those by ancient Egyptian or Ethiopian queens) have been selected primarily for their historical significance, or to celebrate little-known landmarks of achievement. Most, however, have been chosen for their literary qualities, making the anthology a source of continual pleasure and surprise. (...) The cumulative power of this monumental and absorbing anthology stems from the clarity and vibrancy of the voices it assembles. While effectively dismissing the equation of oppression with 'voicelessness', it restores marginalized or isolated writers to the centre of their own rich, resilient and truly international tradition.\"<ref name=Jaggi />\n\nThe anthology was included in ''Sacred Fire: \"QBR\" 100 Essential Black Books'',<ref>Max Rodriguez, [https://books.google.com/books/about/Sacred_Fire.html?id=FDxEAAAAMAAJ ''Sacred Fire: \"QBR\" 100 Essential Black Books''], University of Michigan, 1999.</ref> which said: <blockquote>\"''Daughters of Africa'' is a monumental achievement because it is the most comprehensive international anthology of oral and written literature by women of African descent ever attempted. (...) The success of the collection is that it clearly illustrates why all women of African descent are connected by showing how closely related are the obstacles, the chasms of cultural indifference, and the disheartening racial and sexual dilemmas they faced. In so doing, the collection captures the range of their singular and combined accomplishments.\n\n''Daughters of Africa''\u2032s accomplishment lies in its glorious portrayal of the richness and magnitude of the spiritual well from which we've all drawn inspiration and to where we've all gone for sustenance, and as such, it is a stunning literary masterpiece.\"<ref name=B&N /></blockquote>\n\nThe anthology was on the [[Royal African Society]]'s list of \"50 Books By African Women That Everyone Should Read\",<ref>[http://whatsonafrica.org/50-books-by-african-women-that-everyone-should-read/# \"50 Books by African Women That Everyone Should Read\"], What's On Africa, RAS, 30 June 2014.</ref> was named by ''Ms Afropolitan'' as one of \"7 non-fiction books African feminists should read\",<ref>[http://www.msafropolitan.com/2015/09/non-fiction-books-for-african-feminists.html \"7 non-fiction books African feminists should read\"], ''Ms Afropolitan'', 27 September 2015.</ref> features regularly on many required-reading lists,<ref>Sandra E. Gibbs, [http://www.ncte.org/library/NCTEFiles/Involved/Action/AARI/Young_Adults_Adults.pdf \"National African American Read-In\"], Supplemental List for Young Adults and Adults, Recommended by Black Caucus Members.</ref><!--dead link<ref>Phyllis Stephens [http://www.blackstorytellers.com/late_sister_phyllis_stephens.htm List], Black Storytellers Alliance.</ref>--><ref>[[Nana Darkoa Sekyiamah]], [http://thisisafrica.me/lifestyle/feminist-books-inspired-us-part-1/ \"The feminist books that inspired us \u2013 Part 1\"], This Is Africa, 24 February 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.blackpastblog.org/2012/08/thinking-of-travel-armchair-and.html \"Thinking of Travel: Armchair and Otherwise\"], [[BlackPast.org]], 2 August 2012.</ref><ref>Yinka Sunmonu, [http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/bookshelf-cultural-collection \"Bookshelf: A Cultural Collection\"], ''[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]'', 26 December 2015.</ref><ref>[https://canonofonesown.com/2016/03/18/womens-classic-literature-event-questionnaire/ \"Women\u2019s Classic Literature Event Questionnaire\"], A Canon Of One's Own, 18 March 2016.</ref> and in the words of Kinna Likimani: \"It remains the ultimate guide to women writers of African descent.\"<ref name=KinnaReads />\n\n==Contributors==\nMore than 200 women are featured in ''Daughters of Africa'', including:\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Opal Palmer Adisa]]\n* [[Abena Adomako]]\n* [[Ama Ata Aidoo]]\n* [[Grace Akello]]\n* [[Zaynab Alkali]]\n* [[Ifi Amadiume]]\n* [[Maya Angelou]]\n* [[Red Jordan Arobateau]]<ref>Red Jordan Arobateau, [https://books.google.com/books?id=npauBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=%22Daughters+of+Africa%22+%22margaret+busby%22&source=bl&ots=4PZoGxcaHC&sig=fxnwp0VEkqo5NvrpNhevBXYgZVo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CIcBEOgBMBVqFQoTCJ_a55Cmn8cCFUTaGgod8QwMWQ#v=onepage&q=%22Daughters%20of%20Africa%22%20%22margaret%20busby%22&f=false ''The Rich/The Poor In Spirit''] - New Edition, 2013, p. 249.</ref>\n* Iola Ashundie\n* [[Mariama B\u00e2]]\n* [[Baba of Karo|Baba]]\n* [[Toni Cade Bambara]]\n* [[Valerie Belgrave]]\n* [[Gwendolyn B. Bennett]]\n* [[Louise Bennett]]\n* [[Julia Berger]]<ref name=WP />\n* [[Eulalia Bernard]]<ref>Ian I. Smart, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/23022403 \"Eulalia Bernard: A Caribbean Woman Writer and the Dynamics of Liberation\"], ''Letras Femeninas'', Vol. 13, No. 1/2 (1987), pp. 79\u201385.</ref>\n* [[Ayse Bircan]]<ref name=ICA>[http://sounds.bl.uk/Arts-literature-and-performance/ICA-talks/024M-C0095X0941XX-0100V0 \"Tales of Travel, Daughters of Africa\"], [[Institute of Contemporary Arts|ICA]] talks. [[British Library]].</ref><ref>Annette Madden, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gt-e-5H9B7QC&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq=%22ayse+bircan%22&source=bl&ots=sp75idKwjF&sig=wbBJKlZndbUe8DptofvF74wHf3w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijkcWHo9XWAhUGC8AKHbTSBxUQ6AEIZTAM#v=onepage&q=%22ayse%20bircan%22&f=false \"Ayse Bircan: Turkish activist\"], ''In Her Footsteps: 101 Remarkable Black Women from the Queen of Sheba to Queen Latifah'', Berkeley, California: Conari Press, 2000, pp. 56\u201357.</ref>\n* [[Becky Birtha]]\n* [[Valerie Bloom]]\n* [[Marita Bonner]]\n* [[Dionne Brand]]\n* [[Jean Binta Breeze]]\n* [[Virginia Brindis de Salas]]\n* [[Erna Brodber]]\n* [[Gwendolyn Brooks]]\n* [[Barbara Burford]]<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/183020.Barbara_Burford \"Barbara Burford\"], Goodreads.</ref>\n* [[Annie L. Burton]]\n* [[Abena Busia]]<ref>[http://womens-studies.rutgers.edu/for-faculty/219-abena-busia \"Busia, Abena\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304001305/http://womens-studies.rutgers.edu/for-faculty/219-abena-busia |date=2016-03-04 }}, Department of Women's and Gender Studies, Rutgers School of Arts and Sciences.</ref>\n* [[Dinah Anuli Butler]]<ref>Dinah Anuli Butler, [http://representation-matters.tumblr.com/post/152799408079/to-my-father \"To My Father\"], ''Representation Matters'', 6 November 2016.</r