=5571 \"Shades on a Dream \u2014 Vivian Glover\"], BookOxygen.</ref>\n* [[Marita Golden]]\n* [[Jewelle Gomez]]\n* Pilar L\u00f3pez Gonzales\n* [[Lorna Goodison]]\n* Serena Gordon\n* [[Hattie Gossett]]\n* [[Rosa Guy]]\n* [[Lorraine Hansberry]]\n* [[Frances E. W. Harper]]\n* [[Hatshepsut]]\n* [[Iyamide Hazeley]]<ref>Meserette Kentake, [http://kentakepage.com/when-you-have-emptied-our-calabashes-by-iyamide-hazeley/ \"When You Have Emptied Our Calabashes by Iyamide Hazeley\"], 4 May 2015.</ref>\n* [[Bessie Head]]\n* [[Georgina Herrera]]<!--superfluous ref<ref>[http://www.csuchico.edu/cubanabooks/authors/georgina-herrera.shtml \"Georgina Herrera\"], Cubana Books, California State University.</ref>-->\n* [[Saida Herzi]]<ref>Chantal Zabus, [https://books.google.com/books?id=0gAliuK-DzQC&pg=PA122&lpg=PA122&dq=Saida+Herzi+%22daughters+of+africa%22&source=bl&ots=nEDA3nc2I3&sig=Dr4pDfRE2ZQ9Wo4LSzNBOKy5QWg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi1m9yEzdnJAhWH6RQKHeYeCVAQ6AEIJzAC#v=onepage&q=Saida%20Herzi%20%22daughters%20of%20africa%22&f=false \"Between Rights and Rites: Excision on Trial in African Women's Texts and Contexts\"], in Peter H. Marsden, Geoffrey V. Davis (eds), ''Towards a Transcultural Future: Literature and Human Rights in a 'Post'-Colonial World'', Rodopi, 2004, pp. 122\u201323.</ref>\n* [[Merle Hodge]]\n* [[Billie Holiday]]\n* [[bell hooks]]\n* [[Pauline Elizabeth Hopkins]]\n* [[Amelia Blossom House]]<ref>[http://africanactivist.msu.edu/document_metadata.php?objectid=32-130-183E \"AMELIA BLOSSOM HOUSE - DELIVERANCE: sisterhood is universal\"], [[African Activist Archive]].</ref>\n* [[Akasha Gloria Hull|Gloria T. Hull]]\n* [[Marsha Hunt (actress, born 1946)|Marsha Hunt]]\n* [[Kristin Hunter]]\n* [[Zora Neale Hurston]]\n* [[Noni Jabavu]]\n* [[Mattie J. Jackson]]\n* [[Harriet Jacobs]]\n* [[Carolina Maria de Jesus]]\n* [[Alice Perry Johnson]]<ref>Izetta Roberts Cooper, Kyra E. Hicks, [https://books.google.com/books?id=IgOwAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA86&lpg=PA86&dq=%22Alice+Perry+Johnson%22+%22daughters+of+africa%22&source=bl&ots=GwVxO_LJhk&sig=iz-TcxxgDXCnv033NC2lF3CDd0o&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjA-ZqE87rJAhUFWhoKHQuhBfEQ6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=%22Alice%20Perry%20Johnson%22%20%22daughters%20of%20africa%22&f=false ''Liberia: A Visit Through Books''], Lulu.com, 2008, p. 86.</ref><ref>[http://www.tlcafrica.com/death_johnson_alice.htm \"Alice Perry Johnson\"], The Liberian Connection - Africa.</ref>\n* [[Amryl Johnson]]<!--superfluous as she now has an article<ref>Stewart Brown, [https://www.theguardian.com/news/2001/mar/29/guardianobituaries.books \"Amryl Johnson\" (obituary)], ''The Guardian'', 29 March 2001.</ref>-->\n* [[Georgia Douglas Johnson]]\n* [[Claudia Jones]]\n* [[Gayl Jones]]\n* [[Marion Patrick Jones]]\n* [[June Jordan]]\n* [[Jackie Kay]]\n* Kebbedesh\n* [['Masechele Caroline Ntseliseng Khaketla|Caroline Ntseliseng Khaketla]]<ref>Kathleen E. Sheldon, [https://books.google.com/books?id=36BViNOAu3sC&pg=PA117&lpg=PA117&dq=Caroline+Ntseliseng+Khaketla&source=bl&ots=4UfU3Jcp9S&sig=3h7e7bRP80NHglj5k1YSVFAovwg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjehL-WxtnJAhVC8RQKHUwbAWIQ6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=Caroline%20Ntseliseng%20Khaketla&f=false \"Khaketla, Caroline Ntseliseng 'Masechele\"], ''Historical Dictionary of Women in Sub-Saharan Africa'', Scarecrow Press, 2005, pp. 117\u2013118.</ref>\n* [[Yelena Khanga]]\n* [[Jamaica Kincaid]]\n* [[Mwana Kupona]]\n* [[Ellen Kuzwayo]]\n* [[Alda Lara]]\n* [[Nella Larsen]]\n* [[Andrea Lee (author)|Andrea Lee]]\n* [[Audre Lorde]]\n* [[Elise Johnson McDougald]]\n* [[Terry McMillan]]\n* [[Naomi Long Madgett]]\n* [[Lina Magaia]]\n* [[Barbara Makhalisa]]<!--<ref>Emmanuel Chiwome, [https://books.google.com/books?id=hKmCAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA432&lpg=PA432&dq=%22Barbara+Makhalisa%22&source=bl&ots=y0ps05a8pg&sig=iyfRkptlF2QeKvJNTNroTNMRX3c&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwip1JrRhOzNAhUpL8AKHfFvBhgQ6AEIggEwFw#v=onepage&q=%22Barbara%20Makhalisa%22&f=false \"Makhakisa, Barbara\"], in Simon Gikandi (ed.), ''Encyclopedia of African Literature'', Routledge, 2003, pp. 432\u2013433.</ref>-->\n* [[Zindzi Mandela]]\n* [[Paule Marshall]]\n* [[Una Marson]]\n* [[Annette Mbaye d'Erneville|Annette M'baye]]\n* [[Pauline Melville]]\n* [[Louise Meriwether]]\n* [[Gcina Mhlope]]\n* [[Anne Moody]]\n* [[Mary Monroe]]\n* [[Pamela Mordecai]]\n* [[Nancy Morej\u00f3n]]\n* [[Toni Morrison]]\n* [[Mwana Kupona Msham]]\n* [[Micere Githae Mugo]]\n* [[Pauli Murray]]\n* [[Gloria Naylor]]\n* [[Citeku Ndaaya]]\n* Womi Bright Neal\n* [[Lauretta Ngcobo]]\n* [[Grace Nichols]]\n* Nisa\n* [[Rebeka Njau]]\n* [[Flora Nwapa]]\n* [[Sekai Nzenza-Shand|Sekai Nzenza]]\n* [[Grace Ogot]]\n* [[Molara Ogundipe-Leslie]]\n* [[May Opitz]]\n* [[Gabriela Pearse]]<ref>[https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/14169830.Gabriela_Pearse \"Gabriela Pearse\"] at Goodreads.</ref>\n* [[Ann Petry]]\n* [[Marlene Nourbese Philip]]\n* [[J. J. Phillips]]\n* [[Ann Plato]]\n* [[Velma Pollard]]\n* [[Marsha Prescod]]<ref name=ICA />\n* [[Mary Prince]]\n* [[Nancy Gardner Prince|Nancy Prince]]\n* [[Queen of Sheba]]\n* [[Christine Qunta]]<!--<ref>[https://www.poetryfoundation.org/poets/christine-qunta \"Christine Qunta\"] at [[Poetry Foundation]].</ref><ref>[http://whoswho.co.za/christine-qunta-1763 \"Christine Qunta\"], ''Who's Who Southern Africa''.</ref>-->\n* [[Joan Riley]]\n* [[Astrid Roemer]]\n* [[Carolyn Rodgers]]\n* [[Marta Rojas]]<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/1111652.Marta_Rojas \"Marta Rojas\"] at Goodreads.</ref>\n* [[Lucinda Roy]]\n* [[Jacqueline Rudet]]<ref>[http://www.unfinishedhistories.com/interviews/interviewees/jacqueline-rudet/ \"Jacqueline Rudet\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140505054319/http://www.unfinishedhistories.com/interviews/interviewees/jacqueline-rudet/ |date=2014-05-05 }}, Unfinished Histories.</ref>\n* [[Kristina Rungano]]\n* [[Sandi Russell]]<ref>[http://www.sandi-russell.co.uk/news.html Sandi Russell, Jazz Singer, Writer & Educator]. Myspace.com</ref><ref>Diana Collecott, [https://www.theguardian.com/music/2017/aug/14/sandi-russell-obituary \"Sandi Russell obituary\"], ''The Guardian'', 14 August 2017.</ref>\n* [[Sonia Sanchez]]\n* [[Simone Schwarz-Bart]]\n* [[Mary Seacole]]\n* [[Mabel Segun]]\n* [[Olive Senior]]\n* [[Dulcie September]]\n* [[Ntozake Shange]]\n* [[Jenneba Sie Jalloh]]<ref>[https://www.goodreads.com/author/show/8155954.Jenneba_Sie_Jalloh \"Jenneba Sie-Jalloh\"] at Goodreads.</ref>\n* [[Joyce Sikakane]]<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/784754.Joyce_Sikakane \"Joyce Sikakane\"] at Goodreads.</ref><ref>[http://www.encyclopedia.com/women/encyclopedias-almanacs-transcripts-and-maps/sikakane-joyce-nomafa-1943 \"Sikakane, Joyce Nomafa (1943\u2014)\"], Encyclopedia.com.</ref>\n* [[Zulu Sofola]]\n* [[Aminata Sow Fall]]\n* [[Anne Spencer]]\n* [[Eintou Pearl Springer]]\n* [[Maria W. Stewart]]\n* [[Maud Sulter]]\n* [[Efua Sutherland]]\n* [[V\u00e9ronique Tadjo]]\n* [[Susie King Taylor]]\n* [[Lourdes Teodoro]]\n* [[Mary Church Terrell]]\n* [[Lucy Terry]]\n* [[Awa Thiam]]<!--<ref>Charles F. Peterson, [https://books.google.com/books?id=E-3OV4bXteYC&pg=PA137&lpg=PA137&dq=%22awa+thiam%22+%22daughters+of+africa%22&source=bl&ots=4XELmwMtRT&sig=ee3ytlj8vIXnMLzZinsKRfplpxs&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjZ2s7H7rrJAhUGWhoKHY1FA10Q6AEIJTAB#v=onepage&q=%22awa%20thiam%22%20%22daughters%20of%20africa%22&f=false ''Dubois, Fanon, Cabral: The Margins of Elite Anti-colonial Leadership''], Lexington Books, 2007, p. 137, note 55.</ref>-->\n* [[Elean Thomas]]<!--<ref>[[Buzz Johnson]], [https://www.theguardian.com/news/2004/jul/31/guardianobituaries.booksobituaries \"Elean Thomas\" (obituary)], ''The Guardian'', 31 July 2004.</ref>-->\n* [[Miriam Tlali]]\n* [[Sojourner Truth]]\n* [[Harriet Tubman]]\n* [[Adaora Lily Ulasi]]\n* [[Bethany Veney]]\n* [[Charity Waciuma]]\n* [[Alice Walker]]\n* [[Margaret Walker]]\n* [[Michele Wallace]]\n* [[Myriam Warner-Vieyra]]\n* [[Angelina Weld Grimk\u00e9]]\n* [[Ida B. Wells]]\n* [[Dorothy West]]\n* [[Phillis Wheatley]]\n* [[Zoe Wicomb]]\n* [[Sherley Anne Williams]]\n* [[Harriet E. Wilson]]\n* [[Sylvia Wynter]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==Editions==\n* Margaret Busby (ed.), ''Daughters of Africa: An International Anthology of Words and Writings by Women of African Descent from the Ancient Egyptian to the Present''. First edition, London: [[Jonathan Cape]], hardback, 1992 ({{ISBN|978-0224035927}}), 1089 pages.<ref>[https://books.google.co.uk/books/about/Daughters_of_Africa.html?id=Ipq1AAAAIAAJ&redir_esc=y ''Daughters of Africa''] at Google Books.</ref> \n* \u2014 London: [[Vintage Books]], paperback, 1993 ({{ISBN|978-0099224211}}).\n* \u2014 New York: [[Pantheon Books]], hardback, 1992 ({{ISBN|978-0679416340}}).\n* \u2014 New York: [[Ballantine Books|Ballantine/One World Books]], paperback, 1994<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=RlkEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PA64&lpg=PA64&dq=%22Daughters+of+Africa%22+margaret+busby+ballantine+books+%22one+world%22&source=bl&ots=9UPEriIrL0&sig=oLBkO9gsgxC24kc5cjyqTBsZd9w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi84-GLiPDOAhULIMAKHQkNCWcQ6AEIITAB#v=onepage&q=%22Daughters%20of%20Africa%22%20margaret%20busby%20ballantine%20books%20%22one%20world%22&f=false \"Celebrate Black History Month with the many worlds of African Americans from One World Books\"] (Ballantine Books), ''[[The Crisis]]'', Vol. 101, Issue 1, January 1994, p. 64.</ref> ({{ISBN|978-0345382689}}).\n\n==Influence and legacy==\nThe anthology inspired [[Koyo Kouoh]] to edit a German-language equivalent, ''T\u00f6chter Afrikas'', that was published in 1994.<ref>Sean O'Toole (27 January 2020), [https://www.artnews.com/art-news/news/koyo-kouoh-zeitz-museum-shaping-art-2020s-1202676311/ \"Zeitz Museum Director Koyo Kouoh Looks to Transform South Africa's Art Scene\"], ''[[ARTnews]]''.</ref>\n\nIn November 2017 ''[[Wasafiri]]'' magazine included a special feature marking the 25th anniversary of the first publication of ''Daughters of Africa'',<ref>[https://www.wasafiri.org/product/wasafiri-issue-92/ \"Daughters of Africa Anniversary\"], ''Wasafiri'', Issue 92: Winter 2017.</ref> including an interview with the editor by [[Ellah Wakatama Allfrey]],<ref>Ellah Wakatama Allfrey (2017), [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02690055.2017.1350364?journalCode=rwas20 \"An Interview with Margaret Busby\"], ''Wasafiri'', 32:4, pp. 2\u20136, DOI: 10.1080/02690055.2017.1350364.</ref> an article by Candida Lacey<ref>Candida Lacey, [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/02690055.2017.1350365 \"Daughters of Africa \u2013 Twenty-five years later\"], ''Wasafiri'', 32(4), pp. 7\u20138.</ref> and contributions from [[Edwige Ren\u00e9e Dro]], [[Angela Barry]], [[Goretti Kyomuhendo]], [[Nadifa Mohamed]], [[Phillippa Yaa de Villiers]] and [[Ayobami Adebayo]] about the influence of the anthology on them.<ref>Edwige-Ren\u00e9e Dro, Angela Barry, Goretti Kyomuhendo, Nadifa Mohamed, Phillippa Yaa de Villiers & Ayobami Adebayo, [https://www.tandfonline.com/doi/full/10.1080/02690055.2017.1350367 \"Encounters with ''Daughters of Africa'' from around the world\"], ''Wasafiri'', 32(4), pp. 11\u201312.</ref>\n\n===''New Daughters of Africa''===\nIn December 2017, it was announced that a companion volume, entitled '''''New Daughters of Africa''''', had been commissioned from Margaret Busby by [[Myriad Editions]].<ref>Natasha Onwuemezi, [https://www.thebookseller.com/news/myriad-commissions-new-anthology-about-african-women-writers-689486 \"Busby to compile anthology of African women writers\"], ''The Bookseller'', 15 December 2017.</ref> Published in 2019, ''New Daughters of Africa: An international anthology of writing by women of African descent'' features a further 200 writers including [[Andrea Levy]], [[Chimamanda Ngozi Adichie]], [[Aminatta Forna]], [[Bernardine Evaristo]], Ay\u00f2b\u00e1mi Ad\u00e9b\u00e1y\u00f2, [[Imbolo Mbue]], [[Yewande Omotoso]], [[Warsan Shire]], [[Zadie Smith]], [[Phillippa Yaa de Villiers]], and others.<ref>Otosirieze Obi-Young, [https://brittlepaper.com/2018/01/anthology-edited-margaret-busby-collects-writing-200-african-women-generations/ \"Margaret Busby-Edited Anthology to Feature 200 Female Writers Including Adichie, Aminatta Forna, Bernadine Evaristo, Imbolo Mbue, Warsan Shire, Zadie Smith\"], ''[[Brittle Paper]]'', 10 January 2018.</ref><ref name=Myriad>[http://myriadeditions.com/books/new-daughters-of-africa/ ''New Daughters of Africa'' page] at Myriad Editions.</ref><ref>Emily Temple, [https://lithub.com/lit-hubs-most-anticipated-books-of-2019/5/ \"LIT HUB\u2019S MOST ANTICIPATED BOOKS OF 2019\"], ''[[LitHub]]'', 28 December 2018.</ref> It was launched in London at the [[South Bank Centre]] on 9 March at the [[Women of the World Festival|WOW Festival]].<ref>Margaret Busby, [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2019/mar/09/from-ayobami-adebayo-to-zadie-smith-meet-the-new-daughters-of-africa \"From Ay\u00f2b\u00e1mi Ad\u00e9b\u00e1y\u00f2 to Zadie Smith: meet the New Daughters of Africa\"], ''The Guardian'', 9 March 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.southbankcentre.co.uk/whats-on/133410-new-daughters-africa-2019 \"New Daughters of Africa\"], Southbank Centre, 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.jamesmurua.com/new-daughters-of-africa-launches-in-johannesburg-south-africa/ \"'New Daughters of Africa' launches in Johannesburg, South Africa\"], ''James Murua's Literature Blog'', 12 August 2019.</ref>\n\nConnected with the new anthology, the \"Margaret Busby New Daughters of Africa Award\" was announced by the publisher, in partnership with [[SOAS, University of London]], that will benefit an African woman student.<ref>[https://www.soas.ac.uk/news/newsitem138501.html \"Publisher Myriad and SOAS to launch The Margaret Busby New Daughters of Africa Award\"], SOAS, 15 February 2019.</ref><ref>Natasha Onwuemezi, [https://www.thebookseller.com/news/soas-partners-myriad-launch-bursary-scheme-african-women-writers-953941 \"SOAS partners with Myriad to launch bursary scheme for African women writers\"], ''The Bookseller'', 15 February 2019.</ref><ref>[https://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/myriad-and-soas-launch-%C2%A320000-bursary-black-women \"Myriad And SOAS Launch \u00a320,000 Bursary For Black Women\"], ''The Voice'', 21 February 2019.</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* [[Carole Boyce Davies]], [https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA384&lpg=PA384&dq=%22daughters+of+Africa%22+busby&source=bl&ots=uquFWHlGPA&sig=qKqnnB8GkEMtuHZTYYXKAYqh0sg&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CIQBEOgBMBRqFQoTCNy2t97S1ccCFctYFAodGcYCVA#v=onepage&q=%22daughters%20of%20Africa%22%20busby&f=false \"Women and Literature in the African Diaspora\"], in [[Melvin Ember]], Carol R. Ember, Ian Skoggard (eds), ''Encyclopedia of Diasporas: Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World'', Volume 1 (2005), pp.&nbsp;383\u2013392.\n\n==External links==\n* Aubrey, [https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1200700449 \"Daughters of Africa\"], Goodreads, 17 July 2015.\n* Margaret Busby, [http://www.commonwealthwriters.org/granddaughters-of-africa-margaret-busby/ \"Granddaughters of Africa\"], Commonwealth Writers, 19 March 2015.\n* Kinna Likimani, [http://kinnareads.com/2010/09/24/daughters-of-africa-edited-by-margaret-busby/ \"Daughters of Africa edited by Margaret Busby\"], Kinna Reads, 24 September 2010.\n* Meserette Kentake, [http://kentakepage.com/five-inspirational-poems-for-black-women/ \"Five Inspirational Poems for Black Women\"], ''Kentake Page'', 6 March 2016.\n* [https://sounds.bl.uk/Arts-literature-and-performance/ICA-talks/024M-C0095X0941XX-0100V0 \"Tales of Travel, Daughters of Africa\"], ICA Talks (9 October 1992). British Library\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:1992 books]]\n[[Category:Black British literature]]\n[[Category:British anthologies]]\n[[Category:Black feminist books]]\n[[Category:Books about Africa]]\n[[Category:Feminism in Africa]]\n[[Category:Feminist books]]\n[[Category:Literature by women]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Daughters of Africa 1st editon cover.jpg|thumb|UK 1st edition hardback, 1992. Photograph by Suzanne Roden.]]\n{{italic title}}\n'''''Daughters of Africa: An International Anthology of Words and Writings by Women of African Descent from the Ancient Egyptian to the Present''''' is a compilation of [[orature]] and literature by more than 200 women from Africa and the African diaspora, edited and introduced by [[Margaret Busby]],<ref name=Bolden>Tonya Bolden, [https://books.google.com/books?id=-lwEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT13&lpg=PT13&dq=%22daughters+of+africa%22+200+women&source=bl&ots=LVRNaM4dxY&sig=DSC5ZXzFB95-pCQ1FsM4KLyAq5o&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAmoVChMItJe82rygxwIVitYaCh3ziQ9d#v=onepage&q=%22daughters%20of%20africa%22%20200%20women&f=false \"Book Review: Two Types of Revelation \u2013 ''Daughters of Africa''\"], ''[[Black Enterprise]]'', March 1993, p. 12.</ref> who compared the process of assembling the volume to \"trying to catch a flowing river in a calabash\".<ref>\"Introduction\", ''Daughters of Africa'', p. xxix.</ref> First published in 1992,<ref name=KinnaReads>Kinna, [http://kinnareads.com/2010/09/24/daughters-of-africa-edited-by-margaret-busby/ \"Daughters of Africa edited by Margaret Busby\"], Kinna Reads, 24 September 2010.</ref> in London by [[Jonathan Cape]] (having been commissioned by Candida Lacey,<ref>Candida Lacey, [http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/02690055.2017.1350365 \"Daughters of Africa Twenty-five years later\"], ''Wasafiri'', 32(4), November 2017, pp. 7\u20138.</ref> now publisher of [[Myriad Editions]]),<ref>Margaret Busby, [http://www.commonwealthwriters.org/granddaughters-of-africa-margaret-busby/ \"Granddaughters of Africa\"], [[Commonwealth Writers]], 19 March 2015.</ref> and in New York by [[Pantheon Books]], ''Daughters of Africa'' is regarded as a pioneering work,<ref>[http://www.african-writing.com/Sep/africanbritishprofile.htm#top Margaret Busby profile], African Writing in Britain.</ref><ref>[http://www.bocaslitfest.com/awards/henry-swanzy-award/ \"The 2015 Bocas Henry Swanzy Award Recipient: Margaret Busby, OBE\"] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150702024441/http://www.bocaslitfest.com/awards/henry-swanzy-award/ |date=2 July 2015 }}, [[NGC Bocas Lit Fest]].</ref> covering a variety of genres \u2014 including fiction, essays, poetry, drama, memoirs and children's writing \u2014 and more than 1000 pages in extent.<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/book/show/2051521.Daughters_of_Africa \"Daughters of Africa\"], [[Goodreads]].</ref> Arranged chronologically, beginning with traditional oral poetry,<ref>[https://www.newspapers.com/newspage/84478303/ \"Anthology of black women writers printed\"], ''Journal Gazette'' (Mattoon, Illinois), 3 December 1992, p. 19.</ref> it includes work translated from African languages as well as from Dutch, French, German, Portuguese, Russian and Spanish.<ref>[http://whatsonafrica.org/50-books-by-african-women-that-everyone-should-read/ \"50 Books by African Women that Everyone Should Read\"], What's_On Africa, Royal African Society, 30 June 2014.</ref><ref>Meserette Kentake, [http://kentakepage.com/daughters-of-africa/ \"Daughters of Africa\"], Kentake Page, 17 December 2013.</ref>\n\nThe anthology's title derives from an 1831 declaration by [[Maria W. Stewart]] (1803\u20131880), the first [[African-American]] woman to give public lectures, in which she said: \"O, ye daughters of Africa, awake! awake! arise! no longer sleep nor slumber, but distinguish yourselves. Show forth to the world that ye are endowed with noble and exalted faculties.\"<ref>Maria W. Stewart (ed. Marilyn Richardson), [https://books.google.com/books?id=noSOhOOsNuUC&pg=PA30&lpg=PA30&dq=maria+stewart+%22ye+daughters+of+africa%22&source=bl&ots=tuyBxyTqUE&sig=ZYGhcoSnPkaZTe-73tid8AVCvxQ&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CCcQ6AEwAWoVChMIoa6CoLOtxwIVRrUaCh1igw9W#v=onepage&q=maria%20stewart%20%22ye%20daughters%20of%20africa%22&f=false \"Religion And The Pure Principles of Morality, The Sure Foundation On Which We Must Build\"], in ''America's First Black Woman Political Writer: Essays and Speeches''], [[Indiana University Press]], 1987, p. 30.</ref>\n\nA companion volume entitled '''''New Daughters of Africa''''' was published in 2019.<ref name=Myriad />\n\n==Reception==\n''Daughters of Africa'' was widely praised on publication. Reviewing the anthology for Black British newspaper ''The Weekly Journal'', Evie Arup wrote: \"''Daughters of Africa'' is a literary first. Never before has the work of women of African descent world-wide been gathered together in one volume. The breadth of this collection is startling.... This book should be required reading for any student of literature, and a standard reference book in school libraries, and, to paraphrase that well known slogan, 'every home should have one.'\"<ref>Evie Arup, \"Books: Daughters of Africa\", ''The Weekly Journal'' (Issue 29), 12 November 1992, p. 15.</ref> The reviewer from ''[[The Independent]]'', however, observed: \"This book may seem to be about literature but in the end it is as much a testament to language: its power to create attitudes as well as its potency as a means of expression.\"<ref>Patricia Lee, [https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/books/book-review-canon-to-the-right-of-them-canon-to-the-left-daughters-of-africa-ed-margaret-busby-1563049.html \"BOOK REVIEW / Canon to the right of them, canon to the left...\"], ''The Independent'', 12 December 1992.</ref> Described by ''[[The Observer]]'' as a \"glorious fat anthology that makes a history out of a selection, and puts an unsung group of people on the map\",<ref>[[Nicci Gerrard]], \"Anthologies\", ''The Observer'', 29 November 1992.</ref> according to ''[[Library Journal]]'', it is \"an invaluable text for courses on women writers and writers of African descent\",<ref name=B&N>[http://www.barnesandnoble.com/w/daughters-of-africa-margaret-busby/1002938755#productInfoTabs \"Daughters of Africa: An International Anthology of Words and Writings by Women of African Descent and from the Ancient Egyptian to the Present\"], Editorial Reviews, Barnes & Noble.</ref> and Keneth Kinnamon in ''[[Callaloo (journal)|Callaloo]]'' saw it as \"impressive\", noting: \"Brief headnotes and long bibliographies enhance the value of this important volume.\"<ref>Keneth Kinnamon, \"Anthologies of African-American Literature from 1845 to 1994\", in ''Callaloo'', Vol. 20, No. 2 (Spring 1997), p. 468.</ref> [[Lorna Sage]] in the ''Independent on Sunday'' concluded that \"''Daughters of Africa'' has a paradoxical universality\",<ref>Lorna Sage, \"Deep roots in an impossible homeland\", The Sunday Review, ''Independent on Sunday'', 3 January 1993, p. 21.</ref> while ''[[The Washington Post Book World]]'' called it: \"A magnificent starting place for any reader interested in becoming part of the collective enterprise of discovering and uncovering the silent, forgotten, and underrated voices of black women.\"<ref name=WP>[https://www.washingtonpost.com/archive/entertainment/books/1994/02/06/new-in-paperback/438e9308-0e92-44ef-a403-3fde2d87806a/ \"New in Paperback\"], ''The Washington Post'', 6 February 1994.</ref><ref>Shereen Ali, [http://m.guardian.co.tt/lifestyle/2015-04-29/sharing-our-voices \"Sharing Our Voices\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180802132012/http://m.guardian.co.tt/lifestyle/2015-04-29/sharing-our-voices |date=2018-08-02 }}, ''[[Trinidad and Tobago Guardian]]'', 29 April 2015.</ref>  The reviewer for ''[[Black Enterprise]]'' wrote: \"It is a landmark anthology.... Busby's first-of-a-kind anthology is a poignant reminder of how vast and varied the body of black women's writing is.\"<ref name=Bolden /> It has also been called \"groundbreaking\",<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/profile/margaret-busby Margaret Busby profile], ''[[The Guardian]]''.</ref> \"one of the most significant assemblages of writers across the diaspora\"<ref>Carol Boyce Davies, [https://books.google.com/books?id=7QEjPVyd9YMC&pg=PA384&lpg=PA384&dq=%22Daughters+of+Africa%22+%22margaret+busby%22&source=bl&ots=uqtNXKoCPA&sig=5BNdSUI3ahIcdmpA-st1pgEJ5mk&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CJIBEOgBMBhqFQoTCJ_a55Cmn8cCFUTaGgod8QwMWQ#v=onepage&q=%22Daughters%20of%20Africa%22%20%22margaret%20busby%22&f=false \"Women and Literature in the African Diaspora\"], in Melvin Ember, Carol R. Ember, Ian Skoggard (eds), ''Encyclopedia of Diasporas: Immigrant and Refugee Cultures Around the World, Volume 1'', Springer Science and Business Media Inc., 2005, p. 384.</ref> and \"the ultimate reference guide to the writing of 'daughters of Africa'\".<ref>Sharmilla Beezmohun, [http://www.wasafiri.org/pages/content/index.asp?PageID=307 \"Twenty-Five most influential books\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304084050/http://www.wasafiri.org/pages/content/index.asp?PageID=307 |date=2016-03-04 }}, ''[[Wasafiri]]'', 2009.</ref>\n\nThe ''[[Times Literary Supplement]]'' review by [[Maya Jaggi]] stated: \"With rare exceptions, anthologies of black writing and of women's writing have given the impression that there was very little literary endeavour by black women before the 1980s. Margaret Busby's impressive and imaginative selection of 'words and writings', ''Daughters of Africa'', finally destroys that misconception, while tracing continuities within a tradition of women's writing, deriving from Africa yet stretching across continents and centuries.\"<ref name=Jaggi>Maya Jaggi, \"Ain't I a woman\", ''The Times Literary Supplement'', 11 December 1992.</ref> Jaggi goes on to say: \"Some writings (such as those by ancient Egyptian or Ethiopian queens) have been selected primarily for their historical significance, or to celebrate little-known landmarks of achievement. Most, however, have been chosen for their literary qualities, making the anthology a source of continual pleasure and surprise. (...) The cumulative power of this monumental and absorbing anthology stems from the clarity and vibrancy of the voices it assembles. While effectively dismissing the equation of oppression with 'voicelessness', it restores marginalized or isolated writers to the centre of their own rich, resilient and truly international tradition.\"<ref name=Jaggi />\n\nThe anthology was included in ''Sacred Fire: \"QBR\" 100 Essential Black Books'',<ref>Max Rodriguez, [https://books.google.com/books/about/Sacred_Fire.html?id=FDxEAAAAMAAJ ''Sacred Fire: \"QBR\" 100 Essential Black Books''], University of Michigan, 1999.</ref> which said: <blockquote>\"''Daughters of Africa'' is a monumental achievement because it is the most comprehensive international anthology of oral and written literature by women of African descent ever attempted. (...) The success of the collection is that it clearly illustrates why all women of African descent are connected by showing how closely related are the obstacles, the chasms of cultural indifference, and the disheartening racial and sexual dilemmas they faced. In so doing, the collection captures the range of their singular and combined accomplishments.\n\n''Daughters of Africa''\u2032s accomplishment lies in its glorious portrayal of the richness and magnitude of the spiritual well from which we've all drawn inspiration and to where we've all gone for sustenance, and as such, it is a stunning literary masterpiece.\"<ref name=B&N /></blockquote>\n\nThe anthology was on the [[Royal African Society]]'s list of \"50 Books By African Women That Everyone Should Read\",<ref>[http://whatsonafrica.org/50-books-by-african-women-that-everyone-should-read/# \"50 Books by African Women That Everyone Should Read\"], What's On Africa, RAS, 30 June 2014.</ref> was named by ''Ms Afropolitan'' as one of \"7 non-fiction books African feminists should read\",<ref>[http://www.msafropolitan.com/2015/09/non-fiction-books-for-african-feminists.html \"7 non-fiction books African feminists should read\"], ''Ms Afropolitan'', 27 September 2015.</ref> features regularly on many required-reading lists,<ref>Sandra E. Gibbs, [http://www.ncte.org/library/NCTEFiles/Involved/Action/AARI/Young_Adults_Adults.pdf \"National African American Read-In\"], Supplemental List for Young Adults and Adults, Recommended by Black Caucus Members.</ref><!--dead link<ref>Phyllis Stephens [http://www.blackstorytellers.com/late_sister_phyllis_stephens.htm List], Black Storytellers Alliance.</ref>--><ref>[[Nana Darkoa Sekyiamah]], [http://thisisafrica.me/lifestyle/feminist-books-inspired-us-part-1/ \"The feminist books that inspired us \u2013 Part 1\"], This Is Africa, 24 February 2015.</ref><ref>[http://www.blackpastblog.org/2012/08/thinking-of-travel-armchair-and.html \"Thinking of Travel: Armchair and Otherwise\"], [[BlackPast.org]], 2 August 2012.</ref><ref>Yinka Sunmonu, [http://www.voice-online.co.uk/article/bookshelf-cultural-collection \"Bookshelf: A Cultural Collection\"], ''[[The Voice (British newspaper)|The Voice]]'', 26 December 2015.</ref><ref>[https://canonofonesown.com/2016/03/18/womens-classic-literature-event-questionnaire/ \"Women\u2019s Classic Literature Event Questionnaire\"], A Canon Of One's Own, 18 March 2016.</ref> and in the words of Kinna Likimani: \"It remains the ultimate guide to women writers of African descent.\"<ref name=KinnaReads />\n\n==Contributors==\nMore than 200 women are featured in ''Daughters of Africa'', including:\n{{div col|colwidth=15em}}\n* [[Opal Palmer Adisa]]\n* [[Abena Adomako]]\n* [[Ama Ata Aidoo]]\n* [[Grace Akello]]\n* [[Zaynab Alkali]]\n* [[Ifi Amadiume]]\n* [[Maya Angelou]]\n* [[Red Jordan Arobateau]]<ref>Red Jordan Arobateau, [https://books.google.com/books?id=npauBgAAQBAJ&pg=PA249&lpg=PA249&dq=%22Daughters+of+Africa%22+%22margaret+busby%22&source=bl&ots=4PZoGxcaHC&sig=fxnwp0VEkqo5NvrpNhevBXYgZVo&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0CIcBEOgBMBVqFQoTCJ_a55Cmn8cCFUTaGgod8QwMWQ#v=onepage&q=%22Daughters%20of%20Africa%22%20%22margaret%20busby%22&f=false ''The Rich/The Poor In Spirit''] - New Edition, 2013, p. 249.</ref>\n* Iola Ashundie\n* [[Mariama B\u00e2]]\n* [[Baba of Karo|Baba]]\n* [[Toni Cade Bambara]]\n* [[Valerie Belgrave]]\n* [[Gwendolyn B. Bennett]]\n* [[Louise Bennett]]\n* [[Julia Berger]]<ref name=WP />\n* [[Eulalia Bernard]]<ref>Ian I. Smart, [https://www.jstor.org/stable/23022403 \"Eulalia Bernard: A Caribbean Woman Writer and the Dynamics of Liberation\"], ''Letras Femeninas'', Vol. 13, No. 1/2 (1987), pp. 79\u201385.</ref>\n* [[Ayse Bircan]]<ref name=ICA>[http://sounds.bl.uk/Arts-literature-and-performance/ICA-talks/024M-C0095X0941XX-0100V0 \"Tales of Travel, Daughters of Africa\"], [[Institute of Contemporary Arts|ICA]] talks. [[British Library]].</ref><ref>Annette Madden, [https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=gt-e-5H9B7QC&pg=PA56&lpg=PA56&dq=%22ayse+bircan%22&source=bl&ots=sp75idKwjF&sig=wbBJKlZndbUe8DptofvF74wHf3w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwijkcWHo9XWAhUGC8AKHbTSBxUQ6AEIZTAM#v=onepage&q=%22ayse%20bircan%22&f=false \"Ayse Bircan: Turkish activist\"], ''In Her Footsteps: 101 Remarkable Black Women from the Queen of Sheba to Queen Latifah'', Berkeley, California: Conari Press, 2000, pp. 56\u201357.</ref>\n* [[Becky Birtha]]\n* [[Valerie Bloom]]\n* [[Marita Bonner]]\n* [[Dionne Brand]]\n* [[Jean Binta Breeze]]\n* [[Virginia Brindis de Salas]]\n* [[Erna Brodber]]\n* [[Gwendolyn Brooks]]\n* [[Barbara Burford]]<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/183020.Barbara_Burford \"Barbara Burford\"], Goodreads.</ref>\n* [[Annie L. Burton]]\n* [[Abena Busia]]<ref>[http://womens-studies.rutgers.edu/for-faculty/219-abena-busia \"Busia, Abena\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160304001305/http://womens-studies.rutgers.edu/for-faculty/219-abena-busia |date=2016-03-04 }}, Department of Women's and Gender Studies, Rutgers School of Arts and Sciences.</ref>\n* [[Dinah Anuli Butler]]<ref>Dinah Anuli Butler, [http://representation-matters.tumblr.com/post/152799408079/to-my-father \"To My Father\"], ''Representation Matters'', 6 November 2016.</ref>\n* [[Octavia E. Butler]]\n* [[Joan Cambridge]]<ref>[http://www.bookclubforum.co.uk/community/index.php?/topic/13245-a-book-blog-by-books-do-furnish-a-room/&page=4&tab=comments#comment-441624 \"Clarise Cumberbatch Want to go Home by Joan Cambridge\"], Books do furnish a room, 31 August 2015.</ref>\n* [[A\u00edda Cartagena Portalat\u00edn]]\n* [[Adelaide Casely-Hayford]]\n* [[Gladys Casely-Hayford]]\n* [[Marie Chauvet]]\n* [[Alice Childress]]\n* [[Michelle Cliff]]\n* [[Lucille Clifton]]\n* [[Merle Collins]]\n* [[Maryse Cond\u00e9]]\n* [[Anna Julia Cooper]]\n* [[J. California Cooper]]\n* [[Jayne Cortez]]\n* [[Christine Craig]]\n* [[Jane Tapsubei Creider]]<ref>[http://www.goodreads.com/author/show/892877.Jane_Tapsubei_Creider \"Jane Tapsubei Creider\"] at Goodreads.</ref>\n* [[Tsitsi Dangarembga]]\n* [[Angela Davis]]\n* [[Thadious M. Davis]]<ref>[https://www.english.upenn.edu/people/thadious-davis \"Thadious M. Davis\"], Department of English, University of Pennsylvania.</ref>\n* [[No\u00e9mia de Sousa]]\n* [[Lucy Delaney]]\n* [[Nafissatou Niang Diallo|Nafissatou Diallo]]\n* [[Rita Dove]]\n* [[Mabel Dove-Danquah]]\n* [[Kate Drumgoold]]\n* [[Alice Dunbar-Nelson]]\n* [[Zee Edgell]]\n* Angelika Einsenbrandt\n* [[Zilpha Elaw]]\n* Old Elizabeth\n* [[Buchi Emecheta]]\n* [[Alda do Espirito Santo]]\n* [[Mari Evans]]\n* [[Jessie Redmon Fauset]]\n* [[Charlotte Forten Grimk\u00e9]]\n* [[Aline Fran\u00e7a]]<ref>Femi Ojo-Ade, [https://books.google.com/books?id=8k_DnWuLoS4C&pg=PA247&lpg=PA247&dq=%22Aline+Franca%22&source=bl&ots=y-CBSXPdij&sig=s2r6783FcIXlURHyXOvXd1CV91c&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiR6YjahezNAhUGLsAKHRBbB0cQ6AEIeDAQ#v=onepage&q=%22Aline%20Franca%22&f=false \"Interview with Aline Fran\u00e7a, Afro-Brazilian Woman Writer\"], in ''Being Black, Being Human: More Essays on Black Culture'', Africa World Press, 1996, pp. 247\u2013266.</ref>\n* Henrietta Fullor\n* [[Amy Jacques Garvey]]\n* [[Beryl Gilroy]]\n* [[Nikki Giovanni]]\n* [[Vivian Glover]]<ref>[http://bookoxygen.com/?p=5571 \"Shades on a Dream \u2014 Vivian Glover\"], BookOxygen.</ref>\n* [[Marita Golden]]\n* [[Jewelle Gomez]]\n* Pilar L\u00f3pez Gonzales\n* [[Lorna Goodison]]\n* Serena Gordon\n* [[Hattie Gossett]]\n* [[